Date:    30 Apr 92 11:57:13 +0000
From:    bontchev@fbihh.informatik.uni-hamburg.de (Vesselin Bontchev)
Subject: Re: Bug in TBSCAN/VSIG9203+ (PC)

rslade@cue.bc.ca (Robert Slade) writes:

> However, the VSIG9203 AND 9204 distributions have not worked properly
> with TBSCAN (at least, not with TBSCAN30 and 33.)  Concatenating the
> files with the DOS copy command, as suggested in the documentation,
> results in a message about an error in line 1949 (for 9204) which is
> in the COMPRSCA section, and seems to be a syntactically valid listing
> for COMPACK compression.

> In testing, I also found that, even with the offending lines removed, TBSCAN
> does not give any warning of the compressed files.

> For comparison purposes, HTSCAN, although somewhat slower, gives no error
> messages for the concatenated file, and does correctly identify compressed
> files.

You are right. TbScan has many other bugs, which cause it to not
always detect the signatures that are listed in the signature file.
The main reason for the bugs is that the scanner tries to be too smart
and to trace the virus entry point with a built-in debugger. It is
indeed extremely fast, but most people need a scanner that finds
viruses, not one that can traverse the directory tree faster than any
other... :-) As opposed to TbScan, HTScan plainly scans the whole
file, without doing any tricks. (Well, in fact, it does use one trick
- - the Boyer-Moor fast string searching algorithm.) HTScan is roughly
three times slower than TBScan, but does exactly what it is supposed
to do.

Regards,
Vesselin
