Date:    30 Apr 92 12:20:52 +0000
From:    bontchev@fbihh.informatik.uni-hamburg.de (Vesselin Bontchev)
Subject: Re: misconceptions about CRC in DDJ

TYETISER@ssw02.ab.umd.edu (Tarkan Yetiser) writes:

>      I take exception to Mark R. Nelson's statement in File
> Verification Using CRC, May 1992 that "it is possible that an
> exceptionally clever virus will be able to defeat it [CRCMAN
> verification]." He then continues, "Further modifications to the
> program would improve its ability to fight viruses. For example,
> just storing the length of the file along with its CRC would make
> a virus programmer's job much more difficult, if not impossible."

The possibility to write a virus which forges CRCs has been discussed
a lot about four years ago, but it was before the stealth file
infectors appeared... I'm surprised that people still seem to ignore
some basic things...

>      On page 65, Mr. Nelson also states, "The challenge to the
> virus programmer would then be to add new bytes to the end of the
> file so that the original CRC was restored." This is not only
> misleading but also demonstrates that Mr. Nelson is not familiar
> with a class of viruses known as "stealth" viruses. It is not

Indeed. Mr. Nelson is also wrong is several other obvious ways. For
instance, a virus does not necessarily increase the file size, even if
it is not active in memory (Number of the Beast, 1963, Zero Hunter,
Lehigh, Darth Vader, Int13, etc.). Also, it does not need to "add new
bytes" in order to preserve the file's CRC. I have seen a program
which used to modify COMMAND.COM in such a way that it prints the
message "FluShot is silly. Press any key" and wait for a keypress when
executed. All this without modifying the file's size, date, time, or
checksum. The checksum method that has been targetted by this program
was the method used by FluShot+, which is not a CRC, but the same can
be done for a CRC-based checksum.

> necessary for a virus to forge a scheme like CRC-32 to evade
> detection. There are currently a number of viruses (e.g. 4096,
> Fish-6, 512) that fool all such schemes, including those that
> employ cryptographic checksums. It might surprise Mr. Nelson that
> none of these viruses attempt a direct attack on checksum
> algorithms, but they still succeed in almost every case!

Oh, in fact the stealth file infectors have been created to attack
exactly integrity checkers, just as the fast infectors have been
created to attack scanners and the tunneling viruses have been created
to attack monitoring programs. The historically first stealth file
infector (The Number of the Beast) appeared in Sofia soon after a
speech of mine about the virus prevention techniques, which stressed
that the integrity checkers are the strongest line of defense... :-)

Besides, there are other possible kinds of attack against the
integrity checkers.

>      For any detection mechanism to work against such beasts, the
> verifier must first establish a secure channel between the objects
> on the disk and its memory buffers. The reason is simple: Stealth

Correct. Unfortunately, there's no way to establish such a secure
channel without hardware-supported memory protection.

>      This does not mean that CRC-32 and such schemes cannot be used
> to implement an integrity checker. In fact, they are quite adequate
> as far as catching modifications, as long as the verifier can get
> to the actual contents of the objects on the disk. If a stealth

Yes, but they have to be implemented correctly, and to be aware of
some methods that can be used by the viruses to attack them. Also,
there should no way for the virus to deduce the polinomial on which
the CRC is based, in order to prevent the CRC-forging based attacks.
Yisrael Radai has published several excellent papers on this subject.

> virus is active in memory, other measures must be taken to gain
> untampered access to the disk. Under MS/PC DOS, this is not as
> trivial as it sounds; and it may be one of the reasons why there

Under MS/PC DOS it is even impossible, since to memory protection
mechanisms exist.

> Home-made solutions such as CRCMAN are simply not adequate. Mr.

Of course.

> Nelson should have at least advised his readers to boot from a
> clean, write-protected floppy diskette and then run CRCMAN from the
> same diskette (in case the copy on the hard disk is infected).

Yes, this is the only secure way to make sure that there's no virus in
memory when the integrity checker is being run. Unfortunately, most
users find this requirement to be too inconveniencing...

Regards,
Vesselin
