Date:    Wed, 29 Apr 92 15:31:04 -0500
From:    Werner Uhrig <werner@rascal.ics.utexas.edu>
Subject: Re: Why a good virus is a bad idea?

> I am writing an article about the possibility to use virus techniques
> for something useful. I am already aware with Dr. Cohen's ideas on
> this subject. I am also aware that almost everybody else considers
> this to be a bad idea. I would like to present a detailed, objective
> and non-biased look on the subject. So, could you please send me a
> short note, indicating why you consider the usage of virus techniques
> to be a bad idea.

> If somebody can think about other arguments why a "good" virus is a
> bad idea, please e-mail them to me.

	why waste the time if there are no arguments given why this
	should be considered a "good idea"? (There are none?  well,
	we are done then already...)

	There is no such thing as a "good virus"; your (pro-)position
	is flawed (ill thought out?) in that you are using the terms
	"virus techniques" and "useful" without explanation.  You may
	be thinking of "the intention justifies the means", but
	that is a dangerous line of thought, and experiments along
	that line are likely to see you in disrepute (and in some
	countries, in court).

	a virus is like a visitor who neither announces himself
	nor asks permission.  How would you like me to surreptitiously
	scan all your (private) correspondence?  reason: to correct
	your English/German spelling and grammar.  (I dislike
	analogies, but they do help to make a point sometimes).

	We are all executing lots of code on our computers about
	the purpose and function (details) we know little, and
	which often enough does "unexpected" things (a bug is
	just another kind of virus).  For example, we are using
	anti-virus scanners which modify virus-infected (or suspected)
	files 'on the fly'; when "a mistake" happens, we will not
	be happy, but we will 'understand' to a certain extent;
	however, if someone's "friendly virus" had installed itself
	into my system "to look out for me," and was the cause of
	wrecking my files, a simple "oops, I meant well" won't do.

			     -----------

	What you probably want to do is to define "positive goals"
	that one might want to achieve with programming techniques
	that are "virus-like", but my advice would be to avoid the
	term "virus" completely; leave it alone as a term with negative
	connotations unquestioned...

	have you ever heard of a human immunization that spreads
	"virus-like"?  I haven't, but even if it was possible, who
	would/should take the responsibility to consider the whole
	world as their private laboratory...?!?


